This patch works for the case if a thread function returning not NULL exits before a join. But in a case when the thread function returning NULL exits before join, the current pthread_join will return ESRCH, which is different from the standard pthread_join. For example, the following code:

void* ThreadFunc(void* param)
{
    printf("thread ends\n");
    return NULL;
}

int main()
{
    pthread_t th, th2;
    pthread_create(&th, NULL, ThreadFunc, NULL);

    sleep(1);
    printf("main function ends\n");
    int err = pthread_join(th, NULL);

    printf("err no is: %d (%m)\n",err);
    return 1;
}

the err no in Linux gcc is 0 (not ESRCH), but in current ThreadX will be ESRCH.

It is a bit difficult to make the current pthread_join works exactly the same as the standard one, so I give +1 as long as it works for now.

I think I would have refactored FIFOs so you could literally include 2 FIFOs here.  Doing this way through copy/paste means a bunch of duplicate code.

I.e.  in fifo.h

    typedef struct
    {
        TX_QUEUE        queueCtl;                   ///< ThreadX queue control block
        FifoItem_t      queueSpace[LE_CONFIG_FIFO_QUEUE_LENGTH];  ///< Space for the
 FIFO queue
                                                              ///< items.
        le_mutex_Ref_t  readLock;                   ///< Lock to read from the queue

        size_t          offset;                     ///< Read offset into head item
        uint32_t        readers;                    ///< Number of readers on FIFO
        uint32_t        writers;                    ///< Number of writers on FIFO
    } RawFifo_t;

In fifo.c

    typedef struct
    {
        fd_DeviceObj_t deviceObj;
        le_sem_Ref_t   openSem;
        RawFifo_t      fifo;
    } FifoDeviceObj_t;

Then here:

    typedef struct
    {
        fd_DeviceObj_t deviceObj;
        le_sem_Ref_t   openSem;
        RawFifo_t      c2sFifo;
        RawFifo_t      s2cFifo;
    } PipeDeviceObj_t;

If pipes were literally a pair of FIFOs, this function could be reduced to something like:

    PipeDeviceObj_t *deviceObjPtr = CONTAINER_OF(filePtr->devicePtr, PipeDeviceObj_t, deviceObj);

    if (filePtr->flags & PIPE_SERVER)
    {
        return fifo_Read(&deviceObjPtr->c2sFifo);
    }
    else
    {
        return fifo_Read(&deviceObjPtr->s2cFifo);
    }

I think it would be better to not combine create and open.  Have create return 0 (success) or -1 (failure), then in client:

    int fd = le_fd_Open(pathname, flags | PIPE_CLIENT);

in server

    int fd = le_fd_Open(pathname, flags | PIPE_SERVER);

Combining the two forces the server flags, which may not be desired.

